In[18]:
def plot_exp_results(filename_pattern, results_dir='results'):
    fig = None
    result_files = glob.glob(os.path.join(results_dir, filename_pattern))
    result_files.sort()
    if len(result_files) == 0:
        print(f'No results found for pattern {filename_pattern}.', file=sys.stderr)
        return
    for filepath in result_files:
        m = re.match('exp\d_(\d_)?(.*)\.json', os.path.basename(filepath))
        cfg, fit_res = load_experiment(filepath)
        fig, axes = plot_fit(fit_res, fig, legend=m[2], log_loss=True)
        if 'filters_per_layer' in cfg:
            del cfg['filters_per_layer']
        if 'layers_per_block' in cfg:
            del cfg['layers_per_block']
        print('common config: ', cfg)

      if opt == 'SGD':
           run_name = f'exp2_opt{opt}_mom_0.9_lr{lr}'  # file name
      else:

      experiments.run_experiment(run_name=run_name,

optimizers = ['SGD', 'Adam']
learning_rates = [0.0005, 0.005, 0.05,0.5,1]
for opt in optimizers:
    for lr in learning_rates:
      if opt == 'SGD':
           run_name = f'exp3_opt{opt}_mom_0.9_lr{lr}'  # file name
      else:
           run_name = f'exp3_opt{opt}_lr{lr}'  # file name

      experiments.run_experiment(run_name=run_name,
                                    seed=seed,
                                   optimizer=opt,
                                    bs_train=128,
                                   bs_test=None,
                                   batches=100,
                                    epochs=100,
                                    early_stopping=3,
                                    checkpoints=None,
                                   lr=lr,

4. Regularization

Try to add regularization to your optimization. In particular add L2 regularization.

In[20]:
learning_rates = [0.0005, 0.005]
regularization=[1e-5,1e-4,1e-3]
optimizers = ['SGD', 'Adam']


# regularization
for opt in optimizers:
    for lr in learning_rates:
        for reg in regularization:
            if opt == 'SGD':

5. Pretrained ResNet50

Now use ResNet50 with pretraining (use pretrained=True when you load the model) and run this model on cifar 10.

In[16]:
import torchvision.models as models
import torch.optim as optim

# Define the batch size
batch_size = 32  # you can change this value depending on your GPU capacity

# Create data loaders
train_loader = torch.utils.data.DataLoader(ds_train, batch_size=batch_size, shuffle=True)
val_loader = torch.utils.data.DataLoader(ds_test, batch_size=batch_size, shuffle=False)
dl_test = torch.utils.data.DataLoader(ds_test,batch_size=batch_size, shuffle=False)



# Load the model
model = models.resnet50(pretrained=True)
model.fc = nn.Linear(2048, 10)  # adjust the last layer

# Set the loss function and the optimizer
criterion = nn.CrossEntropyLoss()
optimizer = torch.optim.Adam(model.parameters(), lr=0.0005, weight_decay=1e-3)

# Create an instance of your TorchTrainer class
trainer = training.TorchTrainer(model, criterion, optimizer, device='cuda' if torch.cuda.is_available() else 'cpu')

# Train the model
num_epochs = 10
fit_result = trainer.fit(train_loader, val_loader, num_epochs, print_every=1)
# Switch the model to evaluation mode
model.eval()

# Evaluate on the test set
test_result = trainer.test_epoch(dl_test)

# ========================
print("==================== Test Results ====================")
print(f"Test Accuracy: {test_result.accuracy}")
print(f"Test Loss: {np.mean(test_result.losses)}")
print("======================================================")

# Save the experiment results
experiments.save_experiment("exp6_resnet50_pretrained", './results', config={}, fit_res=fit_result)

# ========================
